[ProMED thanks Dr. Jimenez for providing a summary of his
experimental data and his interpretation and discussion of his
results. Indeed, as Dr. Jimenez points out, WNV circulation and
maintenance in a given geographic area is complex and
multi-factorial. To sustain virus transmission, the hosts must
develop a viremia of long enough duration and high enough magnitude
to infect competent vectors. Populations of susceptible hosts and
vector mosquitoes must be abundant enough for on-going transmission
to occur. Field studies that implicate which vertebrate hosts and
mosquito species are associated with an outbreak must be followed by
laboratory experiments that establish host capacity and vector
competence, accompanied by determination of viral virulence and
genetic composition and variability. The approach requires
integration of sound field ecology, laboratory experimentation and
molecular virology.

An image of the red-legged partridges (_Alectoris rufa_) can be
accessed at
<http://bobperry.smugmug.com/gallery/1010206#46754496_Pnevn>. - Mod.TY]
